==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*ajja-'', from Indo-European ''*oh<font size="-2"><sub>2</sub></font>ujom'' (stem ''*oh<font size="-2"><sub>2</sub></font>ujo-'').

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[ei]] (Dutch [[ei]]), Old High German [[ei]] (German [[Ei]]), Old Norse [[egg]] (English [[egg]], Swedish [[ägg]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ωον|ᾠόν]], Latin [[ovum]] (French [[oeuf]]), Celtic ''*awio-'' (Welsh [[wy]]), Slavic ''*aje'' (Old Church Slavonic [[аице]], Russian [[яйцо]]), Armenian [[ձու]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /æ:j/

===Noun===
'''ǣġ''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''ǣġru''')
# an [[egg]]
#:''Ðæt æg getacnaþ ðone halgan hiht.''  The egg signals the holy hope. (Ælfric’s ''Homilies'')

